at|^b@2^*BForcing 1NT Responses ^*N

We will discuss bidding after forcing 1NT responses. 

Point 1:
A 1NT response to 1@h or 1@s could be as weak as 5 or 6 HCP up to 12 points. 
So opener's first job is to limit her hand. 

Let's review hand strengths: 
A MINIMUM opening bid is anything up to about a bad 16 points; 
An INVITATIONAL opener is about 16 to 18;
A STRONG opener is 19+ points. 

(I recommend that you open all  (15-17) 5332 shape, with 1NT. 
This solves some miserable rebid problems)
For example, holding   @sxx   @hAK10xx   @dAxx   @cKQx   (with 15-17 HCP)
1@h - pass - 1@s - pass - ??      you have no good rebid! Open 1NT and not 1@h

So let's assume that opener began with 1@h or 1@s in first or second seat and responder bids 1NT.

In most cases, responder will not have as much as 3-card support for opener’s Major, 
so our rebid structure is designed to keep the bidding low enough to find a fit in a different suit.

Opener must be careful about jumps, else the auction may become very awkward. 
The 3-level is an uncomfortable place to be looking for a fit. |
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


nt||cp|2|at|^b@2

In the following discussion, we assume that responder bids 1NT after your opening 1@h or 1@s bid 

With a ^*uminimum opener^*n (at most 15 points), opener’s rebids are as follows:

a) Rebid the opening Major with a 6-card suit. (Note: with 6 of your Major and a lower-ranking 4-card suit, 
bid the 4-card suit and then rebid the 6-card Major to show a hand with 14-17 points.)
example:   @sKJxxxx    @hAQx   @dQ10x   @cx             opener rebids 2@s.  
With          @sKJxxxx    @hx       @dKQxx    @cKx          also rebid 2@S.
But with    @sKQ10xxx  @hx      @dAQxx    @cKx          bid 2@d, planning to rebid spades on your third bid.

b) If opener has 5+ spades and 4+ hearts, she rebids 2@h 

c) If opener has just a 5-card Major and a balanced hand, she rebids her longer minor. 
With equal strength and length in the minors, I prefer to bid 2@c. 
If opener has specifically 4=5=2=2 shape, she rebids 2@C.  
This, because responder is obligated to bid 1@s if she has 4 of them.  
This is the ONLY time you bid a 2-card minor over a forcing 1NT.
To avoid the problem of rebidding a 2-card suit, some pairs use the Flannery convention, which I do not 
recommend; I am willing to play in the unlikely 2-4 fit to keep 2@d as a natural weak 2.

d) This structure allows responder to correct to 2 of opener’s Major with a doubleton and a hand not strong 
enough to invite game.   Examples: opener’s hand is   
@sQx       @hKQJxx   @dAxx   @cQxx     -- rebid 2@d (equal length but stronger minor **)
@SAQxxx   @hKQxx    @dJxx   @cx        -- rebid 2@h 
@sAQxxx   @hKQx     @dxxx   @cKx       -- rebid 2@d  (your longer minor)

Responder will take a "false preference" with a 2-card support for your Major. 
Example: opener bids 1@S, you the resoponder holding (@s97, @hK10xx, @dQxx, @cJxxx) bid 1NT (forcing), 
opener rebids 2@d, your rebid is 2@s
(** MM: Others may suggest:  "with 3-3 in the minors bid @c's")
