nt||cp|2|at|^b@2
With a ^*umedium opener^*n, opener’s rebids are as follows:

- With a sound 6-card Major that can play for 1 loser opposite a singleton (KQJ9xx or better) and 16-18 starting points, jump rebid your suit.        1@s - 1NT / 3@s
Example:  @sxx   @hKQJ10xx   @dAxx   @cAx         1@h - 1NT / 3@h     NOTE: this is ^*uNON-FORCING^*n 

Responder will pass with something like     @sKxx   @hx   @dJ10xxx   @cQxxx    
but with any doubleton support in a 9-loser hand or better, responder should raise. 
Example: @sKxx   @hxx   @dQJxxx   @cQxx 

If responder has the 3-card limit raise for her 1NT response, she raises to game.  Opener has at worst a 
6 loser hand, and the 3-card limit raise has 8 losers, not quite enough to bid past game. 

The jump rebid of 3 of a Major shows about 5-6 losers. With a ^*ustronger hand^*n (17+), you plan to:
a) Raise 1NT to 2NT with a balanced 5332 hand and 18-19 HCP.      (MM: some suggest with 16-18)

b) Jump-shift  (Game forcing)
Sometimes you will jump-shift into a 3-card minor to establish a GF situation -- Example:
@sAKJ10x   @hxx   @dKJx   @cAKJ    (I would like to open 2NT, but my heart holding convinces me otherwise.) 
If partner has enough strength to bid over 1@S with 1NT, I will bid 3@C at my second turn. 
The absence of a 6th spade and my extra strength both make it wrong to bid 3@s over 1NT.

c) Reverse (1 round force). 
So here is what we do with invitational hands:
Note that a reverse is at least invitational, but still can be very strong:  
1@h - 1NT /2@s   where opener might have a hand like: 
@sKJ10x   @hAKJxx   @dK10x   @cx|
