OK - so what does 1@S - 1NT / 2NT show???
Cliff228: too strong to open 1NT
mitche: With 20, we open 2NT - so this bid shows 18 points, or a very bad 19
Exactly right, Cliff -- it shows a hand too good to open 1NT
Remember that pard promises 6 HCP .. 

So the auction 1@S  1NT / 3NT shows a good 19, 5332 shape, and at least partial stoppers in every suit
It is NOT a shutout bid, since pard can still correct your 3NT to 4 of your Major with 3-card support and a ruffing value

Now, one other sequence: 
You open 1@H and partner bids 1NT
If you play Flannery (I hope you do not. Really), then 1@H - 1NT/ 2@S shows 4 spades, 5 hearts, and about 16 HCP
Otherwise you lose the spade suit. And that is really bad.. 
(now where did I put that blasted spade suit? Under the couch? is it still in the card holder???)

But let's suppose that you don't play Flannery.. 
then there are 2 ways to show a strong hand:
(other than raising 1NT to 2NT) 

- To show a strong unbalanced hand, you may reverse with 2@S over 1@H
(this may show any of a variety of hand patterns, 1 round forcing) 

- Or you may jump-shift into 3 of a minor.. (GF) 
But note, if you bid 3@C or 3@D over 1NT forcing you should have an unbalanced hand. 
Something like this:     @sx   @hKQ10xx   @dKJx   @cAQJx
This is about a minimum hand for this jump shift. 
Since pard did not bid 1@S, you either have a heart or a minor suit fit|
