^*bOther odds and ends^*n:
 
1@S - 1NT / 3@S - shows an invitational (16-18) point hand with 6 spades
and 1@S - 1NT/ 4@S shows a 6+ card suit with about 19-20 points (just below a 2@C opener)

^*bResponder's 3-card limit raise in 2 over 1^*n

Here is the problem:
When you raise 1@S or 1@H to 2, you promise 7-9 dummy points and a 3-card support. 
If you play Bergen raises (I think you should), 
then you have a problem showing this kind of hand:

{|ih|pSA62 HJ97 DAQ94 CT65|at|}|at|


A 3-card support and 10-12 dummy points
What is the answer?
Playing 2 over 1, you can use forcing 1NT to handle this problem. 
Responder bids 1NT, forcing

Here is the point I am driving toward .. 
How do you distinguish between 3- card and 4- card raises of 1@H or 1@S|
