nt||fp||cp|2|cs|1|at|^b@2 

The usual way to do this is as follows:

a) with 3-card support and 7-9 dummy points, raise 1@H (1@S) to 2
b) with 4 card support and 7-9, use a Bergen raise to 3@C
c) with 3-card support and 10-12 HCP, start with 1NT (if you are an unpassed hand)
d) with 4-card support and 10-12 dummy points - if you are an unpassed hand, bid 3@D, Bergen 

e) If you are a passed hand, use DRURY (2@C) to show a 3-card limit raise (10-12 dummy pts)
f) If you are a passed hand with 4-card support and 10-12 dummy points, bid 2@D (Drury)

^*bOpener's responses to Drury 2@C (3-card) and 2@D (4-card) limit raise passed hands are^*n:

- If you opened 1@s weak in third seat, you rebid 2@S 

- If you bid 3@S, you are asking responder to bid game with 11+ or 12 dummy points
  (some people play 3@S rebid by opener as a general slam try. Check with partner)

- If you have a full opener with no slam interest, just bid 4 of your Major.

- ANY NEW SUIT bid by opener is 100% forcing to game and is a genuine second suit; 
  It shows extra values and invites responder to control bid with fitting cards in the second suit

All of the fit-showing bids (3@C, 3@D Bergen, and Drury) 
are ALERTABLE and should be discussed w/partner before using them

(MM: And some use Bergen and or Drury reversed)|
